2026-04-06 02:44:13 - Agent_20260406023840 - INFO - [+] Agent signaled completion: Reviewed 5 CodeQL findings related to ACL update operations called from broker processors handling network requests in Apache RocketMQ. All 5 findings were confirmed as true positives.

Root cause: The ADMIN_CODE set in Permission.java does NOT include UPDATE_AND_CREATE_ACL_CONFIG, DELETE_ACL_CONFIG, or UPDATE_GLOBAL_WHITE_ADDRS_CONFIG request codes. The parse() method in PlainAccessValidator doesn't handle these codes (falls to default:break), leaving resourcePermMap null. In checkPerm(), when needCheckedPermMap is null, the method returns immediately with no permission check. This means any authenticated non-admin user can:

1. Create/update ACL access configs (PlainAccessValidator.java:156) - grant themselves admin privileges
2. Delete ACL access configs (PlainAccessValidator.java:161) - remove admin users
3. Update global whitelist without file path (PlainAccessValidator.java:169) - bypass authentication entirely
4. Update global whitelist with custom file path (PlainAccessValidator.java:173) - target specific ACL files
5. Core PlainPermissionManager implementation (PlainPermissionManager.java:473) - the actual file write that enables auth bypass

The most critical impact is the global whitelist manipulation: once an attacker's IP is added to the global whitelist, validate() returns immediately before any credential check, achieving complete authentication bypass for all future requests.
